ial and postcolonial eras. Her astute analysis of this religious trend sheds light on Nigeria’s contemporary politics, postcolonial statecraft, and the everyday struggles of ordinary citizens coping with poverty, corruption, and inequality. Pentecostalism’s rise is truly global, and Political Spiritualities persuasively argues that Nigeria is a key case in this phenomenon while calling for new ways of thinking about the place of religion in contemporary politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristianity and politicsxNigeria. 0aChristianity and politicszNigeria. 0aPentecostalismxNigeria. 0aPentecostalismxPolitical aspectsxNigeria. 0aPentecostalismxPolitical aspectszNigeria. 0aPentecostalismzNigeria. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  anigeria, pentecostal, religion, spirituality, christianity, conversion, pentecostalism, benjamin, arendt, agamben, foucault, politics, history, nonfiction, inequality, corruption, poverty, postcolonialism, government, social change, colonialism, salvation, promise, redemption, born again, revival, conviction, rupture, political science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226507149423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226507149/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles